{"analysis": "The query groups orders by whether a discount campaign was active and computes the average order value (AOV) for each group. Non-campaign days show an AOV of 12,616.93 JPY across 1,834 orders, while campaign days show an AOV of 9,693.25 JPY across 484 orders. Campaign-day AOV is lower by (12616.93 - 9693.25) / 12616.93 ≈ 23.2%.

The hypothesis states that AOV on discount campaign days is lower than on non-campaign days. The data directly confirms this ordering: campaign AOV < non-campaign AOV. Moreover, the magnitude of the reduction (~23%) falls squarely within the organization-specific expected range of 10–25% lower, consistent with the 'bargain-hunter effect' rule from internal marketing analysis. Sample sizes are reasonably large (484 and 1,834 orders), so the observed difference is unlikely to be noise.

One caveat is that this aggregate comparison does not control for confounds such as product mix, seasonality (e.g., Q4 seasonal spikes), or customer segment composition (VIP vs new). However, the hypothesis as stated is a simple directional comparison of AOV, and the query answers that question directly and affirmatively.", "verdict": "supported", "evidence_summary": "Campaign-day AOV (9,693) is ~23% lower than non-campaign AOV (12,617), matching the hypothesized direction and the expected 10–25% bargain-hunter magnitude."}
